hands_on_practices.problem:
A research team is evaluating a monoclonal Immunoglobulin G (IgG) that binds a tumor-associated antigen on a human carcinoma cell line. In a cell-free assay that contains no leukocytes, they observe target-cell lysis when the antibody is incubated with fresh Normal Human Serum (NHS). They want to determine whether the cytotoxicity is complement-dependent (that is, requires the Complement-Dependent Cytotoxicity (CDC) mechanism), rather than due to other serum factors. Starting from core facts that (i) the classical complement pathway is triggered when IgG bound to antigen recruits complement component $C1$ to initiate the cascade; (ii) the complement cascade requires divalent cations, especially calcium (Ca$^{2+}$) and magnesium (Mg$^{2+}$), for several proteolytic steps; (iii) complement activity is heat-labile and is abrogated by incubation at $56^{\circ}\mathrm{C}$ for $30$ minutes; and (iv) formation of the Membrane Attack Complex (MAC; C$5$b–C$9$) is required for lysis of many nucleated cells in vitro, select the control scheme that most rigorously verifies that observed cytotoxicity is complement-dependent and not due to other serum factors.

Which option best specifies a scientifically sound and sufficient control scheme centered on using heat-inactivated serum, with appropriate companion controls, to attribute lysis specifically to complement?

- A. Perform parallel assays with antibody plus either NHS or heat-inactivated NHS (HI-NHS; $56^{\circ}\mathrm{C}$ for $30$ minutes). Include a no-antibody control with NHS. Conclude that loss of lysis with HI-NHS proves complement dependence.

- B. In a leukocyte-free system, run the following in parallel: 
  ($1$) antibody $+$ NHS; 
  ($2$) antibody $+$ HI-NHS (prepared at $56^{\circ}\mathrm{C}$ for $30$ minutes); 
  ($3$) antibody $+$ HI-NHS reconstituted with purified complement (for example, C$1$–C$9$ at near-physiologic activity); 
  ($4$) antibody $+$ NHS $+$ ethylenediaminetetraacetic acid (EDTA; $10$ mM) to chelate Ca$^{2+}$/Mg$^{2+}$; 
  ($5$) isotype-matched nonbinding antibody $+$ NHS; 
  ($6$) NHS without antibody; 
  ($7$) antibody without serum. Quantify lysis (for example, Lactate Dehydrogenase (LDH) release). Conclude complement dependence only if lysis requires both intact complement and divalent cations and is rescued by reconstitution.

- C. Replace NHS with serum boiled at $95^{\circ}\mathrm{C}$ for $10$ minutes to remove all proteins, compare to NHS in the presence of antibody, and attribute any difference to complement. Optionally add fetal bovine serum as a carrier.

- D. Use antibody $F(ab')_2$ fragments with NHS to avoid Fc-mediated effects, and compare to intact IgG with HI-NHS. If lysis is greater with $F(ab')_2$ $+$ NHS than with IgG $+$ HI-NHS, conclude complement dependence.

Choose the single best option.
